The Complutense University of Madrid, or *Universidad Complutense de Madrid* (UCM), is a [public](/Public_university), [research](/Research_university) institution nestled in [Madrid](/Madrid). Its origins trace back to [Alcalá](/Alcal%C3%A1_de_Henares) in 1293, making it one of the oldest operational universities globally and a decidedly significant academic entity in Spain. It relocated to Madrid in 1836. The university sprawls across the [Ciudad Universitaria district of Madrid](/Ciudad_Universitaria_(Madrid)), with additional grounds in Somosaguas, a neighboring municipality. Its name is a nod to [Complutum](/Complutum), the ancient Roman settlement now an archeological site in [Alcalá de Henares](/Alcal%C3%A1_de_Henares).

With over 86,000 students, it ranks as the eighth [largest non-distance European university by enrollment](/List_of_largest_universities_by_enrollment). A Royal Decree from 1857 designated the [Central University](/The_Central_University_of_Madrid) as the sole authority in Spain capable of conferring [doctorate degrees](/PhD) across the entire [Spanish Empire](/Spanish_Empire). A notable milestone occurred in 1909 when it granted a doctorate to a woman, a rarity for the era. The institution was rebranded as Universidad de Madrid in 1943.

### History

See also: [University of Alcalá](/University_of_Alcal%C3%A1)

Cardinal Cisneros, a figure of considerable influence, orchestrated the expansion of the existing Studium Generale into a substantial university comprising five colleges.

The genesis of this institution can be traced to 20 May 1293, when King [Sancho IV of Castile](/Sancho_IV_of_Castile) issued a royal charter authorizing the [Archbishop of Toledo](/Archbishop_of_Toledo), [Gonzalo Pérez Gudiel](/Gonzalo_P%C3%A9rez_Gudiel), to establish a *studium generale*—the designation for universities at that time—in [Alcalá de Henares](/Alcal%C3%A1_de_Henares). It was christened El Estudio de Escuelas Generales. Later, [Cardinal Cisneros](/Cardinal_Cisneros), a distinguished alumnus, undertook significant land acquisitions and commissioned the construction of numerous buildings. This ambitious project resulted in what is widely considered the first purpose-built [university campus](/University_campus) in history, envisioned as the *Civitas Dei*, or City of God, a title inspired by [Augustine of Hippo](/The_City_of_God_(book)). On 13 April 1499, Cisneros obtained a [papal bull](/Papal_bull) from [Pope Alexander VI](/Pope_Alexander_VI), elevating Complutense to full university status. This papal decree provided international recognition throughout [Christendom](/Christendom) for all degrees conferred by the university. The institution was subsequently renamed *Universitas Complutensis*, a tribute to *Complutum*, the Latin name for [Alcalá de Henares](/Alcal%C3%A1_de_Henares), its original location.

By the 1509–1510 academic year, the Complutense University was structured around five principal schools: Arts and Philosophy, [Theology](/Theology), [Canon Law](/Canon_Law), [Philology](/Philology), and Medicine. [6][7] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Complutense ascended to become a preeminent global center of academic distinction. It attracted and nurtured many of the era's leading minds in science, arts, and politics. [8] To accommodate international students, specialized colleges were established, such as those for [Flemish](/Flemish_people) and Irish students, like the [Irish College of San Jorge at Alcalá de Henares](/Irish_College_at_Alcala).

In 1785, Complutense made history by being among the first universities worldwide to award a [doctorate](/Doctorate) to a woman, [María Isidra de Guzmán y de la Cerda](/Mar%C3%ADa_Isidra_de_Guzm%C3%A1n_y_de_la_Cerda). [9] For context, the [University of Oxford](/University_of_Oxford) didn't admit female scholars until 1920, [10] and the [University of Cambridge](/University_of_Cambridge) didn't grant a PhD to a woman until 1926. [11]

In 1824, [Francisco Tadeo Calomarde](/Francisco_Tadeo_Calomarde) further augmented Complutense by integrating the University of Sigüenza into it. [12] However, by a royal order dated 29 October 1836, Queen Regent [Maria Christina](/Maria_Christina_of_the_Two_Sicilies) dissolved the university in Alcalá and mandated its relocation to Madrid. There, it was initially known as the Literary University, and in 1851, it became the Central University (*Universidad Central*).

[Alfonso XIII](/Alfonso_XIII), the King of Spain, is pictured here with faculty members of the university, including [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein), José Rodríguez Carracido, and [Blas Cabrera y Felipe](/Blas_Cabrera_Felipe), on March 11, 1923.

The Central University bestowed an honorary Doctor of Science degree upon Albert Einstein on 28 February 1923; this was the first such honorary degree [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein) accepted from a European institution. In April 1933, [Fernando de los Ríos](/Fernando_de_los_R%C3%ADos), the Minister for Education and the Arts, announced Einstein's agreement to lead a research institute, to be named the *Instituto Albert Einstein*, under the university's School of Science. [13] Tragically, the escalating political instability across Europe meant Einstein ultimately accepted a comparable position at the [Institute for Advanced Study](/Institute_for_Advanced_Study) in [Princeton, New Jersey](/Princeton,_New_Jersey).

The university experienced significant expansion throughout the 19th century, but its central Madrid facilities became increasingly insufficient. Beyond the growing student body, the university, after its move from [Alcalá](/Alcal%C3%A1_de_Henares), occupied a series of pre-existing structures—largely aristocratic mansions and royal palaces abandoned by their former occupants. While possessing historical charm, these ancient buildings were hardly conducive to modern educational needs. The early 20th century saw students attending philosophy lectures and anatomy lessons in spaces that had recently served as ballrooms and drawing rooms.

This situation began to shift in 1927 when, by royal decree, King [Alfonso XIII](/Alfonso_XIII) allocated state lands near the Palace of [La Moncloa](/La_Moncloa) for the establishment of the University of Madrid. At the time, this encompassed the entire territory between the Royal Palace and the Palace of [El Pardo](/El_Pardo), now known as the "Ciudad Universitaria," or [University City of Madrid](/University_City_of_Madrid).

Engineers, graduates of the Complutense University, are pictured in 1913.

A council appointed by King Alfonso XIII decreed that the new University of Madrid would embody innovative architecture and planning. A delegation of academics embarked on an international tour to study prestigious universities in Europe and North America, intending to synthesize the best elements from both continents to design an ideal academic environment. Their journey included visits to 19 universities in the American Northeast, as well as institutions in Paris, [Lyon](/Lyon), [Oxford](/Oxford), Berlin, [Hamburg](/Hamburg), and numerous other European cities, all in pursuit of the optimal architectural blueprint. However, the prevailing architectural trends of the era ultimately exerted a stronger influence than the academics' visits to institutions like Harvard, the [University of Pennsylvania](/University_of_Pennsylvania), [La Sorbonne](/University_of_Paris), or the [University of Berlin](/University_of_Berlin). While the finalized plans from this period bear little resemblance to the contemporary campus, the surviving buildings from that era—exemplified by the Schools of Medicine, Pharmacy, and Odontology—demonstrate a clear affinity for the German [Bauhaus](/Bauhaus) movement, celebrating structural functionalism and the elegant [utilitarianism](/Utilitarianism) characteristic of the 1920s.

During the 1970s, amidst the political upheaval of the Francisco Franco regime, the University of Madrid underwent a renaming and division. Existing colleges were partitioned between the Complutense University of Madrid and the [Technical University of Madrid](/Technical_University_of_Madrid). When the city of Alcalá de Henares revived its own university within the older campus buildings, it was named [Universidad de Alcalá de Henares](/Universidad_de_Alcal%C3%A1_de_Henares) to clearly differentiate it from Complutense.

### Today

